      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <!--
Comments below by Csaba Kiss and Dániel Balogh (BD) are offered "as is" and do not represent a thoroughly researched or considered opinion.
-->
        <p><pb n="1v"/>svasti<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied>
<lb n="1"/>śarabhapurā<surplus>t</surplus>d vikkramopanata-sāmaṁt<surplus>t</surplus>a-cūḍā-maṇi-prabhā-prasekāmbu<lb break="no" n="2"/>bhir dh<unclear>au</unclear>ta-pāda-yugalo ripu-vilāsinī-sīma<choice>
            <sic>t</sic>
            <corr>n</corr>
          </choice>toddharaṇa-hetur vvasu-vasudhā<!--
BD: this au definitely looks like o; it is not the o-like au that has occurred a few times in other plates. Still, I'm willing to bow to Sircar, let's accept it as an unclear au. Same for the au in line 8.
--><lb break="no" n="3"/>-go-pradaḫ parama-bhāgavato mātā-pit<choice>
            <sic>ri</sic>
            <corr>r̥</corr>
          </choice>-pādānuddhyātaḥ śrī-mahā-jayarājaḥ<!--
L3. visarga indicated with two horizontal strokes (ddhyātaḥ).
--><lb n="4"/>A<unclear>ṁ</unclear>t<surplus>t</surplus>aranālakīya-kada<surplus>ṁ</surplus>mbapadrullake prativāsi-k<unclear>u</unclear>ṭumbinas samā<lb break="no" n="5"/>jñāpayati|<!--
L5. jñāpayati| daṇḍa indicated by visarga-like mark.
--></p>
        <p>viditam astu vo yathāsmābhir ayaṁ grāmas tridaśa-pati-
<lb n="6"/>sadana-sukha-pratiṣṭhā-karo yāvad ravi-śaśi-tār<unclear>ā</unclear>-kiraṇa-pratihata-
					<pb n="2r"/><lb n="7"/>ghorā<choice>
            <sic>d</sic>
            <corr>n</corr>
          </choice>dha-kāra<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> jagad avatiṣṭhate tāvad upabho<choice>
            <sic>jya</sic>
            <corr>gyaḥ</corr>
          </choice> sa-nidhis sopanidh<subst>
            <del rend="corrected">ī</del>
            <add place="overstrike">i</add>
          </subst><!--
L7. BD: I've looked at the facsimile and I don't really think it's a correction of ī to i, but let's believe Sircar. In this inscription i is a circle over the character (often not closed at the left), and ī is an identical circle (also not necessarily closed on the left, see śrī in line 3), with a dot in the middle. The one here has something near the top of the circle, which may be a scratched-out middle dot.
--><lb break="no" n="8"/>r acāṭa-bhaṭa-prāv<choice>
            <sic>ai</sic>
            <corr>e</corr>
          </choice>śya<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> sarvva-kara-visarjjitaẖ k<unclear>au</unclear>tsa-sagotra-brāhmaṇa-kapa<lb break="no" n="9"/>rd<unclear>d</unclear>isvāminas somoparāge mātā-pitror ātmanaś ca puṇyābhiv<choice>
            <sic>ra</sic>
            <corr>r̥</corr>
          </choice>ddha<lb break="no" n="10"/>ye Udaka-pūrvva<unclear>ṁ</unclear> tām<surplus>b</surplus>ra-śāsanenāti<unclear>s</unclear>r̥ṣṭa<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><unclear>|</unclear> <surplus>s</surplus>te yūyam evam upala<!--
L10. D. Balogh: Sircar interprets the mark after atisr̥ṣta as a visarga, but I am quite certain it is a punctuation mark. For a parallel case of punctuation applied before a superfluous word-final s, see IN01019 line 12.
--><lb break="no" n="11"/>bhyā<unclear>s</unclear>yājñā-śravaṇa-vidheyā bhūtvā yathocita-bhoga-bhāgam upanayaṁt<surplus>t</surplus>aḥ sukhaṁ<!--
L11 upanayaṁttaḥ: visarga indicated with two horizontal strokes.
--><lb n="12"/>prativa<supplied reason="omitted">t</supplied>syatha| bhaviṣyataś ca bhūmipān anudarśayati|<!--
L12. both daṇḍas: one horizontal stroke and one dot above, one below.
--></p>
        <lg met="vasantatilakā" n="1">
          <l n="a">dānā<unclear>d vi</unclear>śiṣṭa
							<pb break="no" n="2v"/>
<lb break="no" n="13"/>m anupālanajaṁ purāṇā<surplus>t</surplus></l>
          <l n="b">dharmmeṣu niścita-dhiyaḫ pravada<surplus>ṁ</surplus>nti dharmma<choice>
              <sic>ṁ</sic>
              <corr>M</corr>
            </choice></l>
          <!--
v1b. DB: Sircar prints dharmma (emending to dharmmaM), but notes that "there appear to be an anusvāra sign above rmma and the faint trace of a final m to its right". In the rubbing, the anusvāra is clear; the faint trace to the right of the character is beyond the margin, doesn't look like a halanta M to me, and a halanta M would be inconsistent with the orthography of the plate (compare goptuṁ in the next line), so I prefer to dismiss it as noise.
-->
          <lb n="14"/>
          <l n="c">tasmā<supplied reason="omitted">d</supplied> dvijāya suviśuddha-kula-śrutāya</l>
          <l n="d">dattāṁ bhuvaṁ bhavatu vo mati<lb break="no" n="15"/>r eva goptu<choice>
              <sic>ṁ</sic>
              <corr>M</corr>
            </choice>M</l>
        </lg>
        <ab>
          <del>
            <unclear>matir eva goptuṁ</unclear>
          </del>
          <space/>
        </ab>
        <p>bhavad<choice>
            <sic>v</sic>
            <corr>bh</corr>
          </choice>ir apy eṣā dattir anupāla<lb break="no" n="16"/>yitavyā| vyāsa-gītāṁś cātra ślokān udāharaṁ<surplus>t</surplus>ti|<!--
L16. first daṇḍa: one horizontal stroke and one dot above, one below.
second daṇḍa: two horizontal strokes.
--></p>
        <lg met="indravajrā" n="2">
          <l n="a">agner apatyaṁ <lb n="17"/>prathamaṁ suvarṇṇaṁ</l>
          <!--
v2a. Two horizontal strokes after suvarṇṇaṁ.
-->
          <l n="b">bhūr vvaiṣṇavī sūryya-sutāś ca gāvaḥ</l>
          <!--
v2b. visarga: two horizontal strokes.
-->
          <l n="c">dattās traya<lb break="no" n="18"/>s tena bhavaṁ<surplus>t</surplus>ti lokā</l>
          <l n="d">yaẖ kāñcanaṁ gā<surplus>ṁ</surplus>ñ ca mahīñ ca dadyā<unclear>t</unclear></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="3">
          <l n="a"><pb n="3r"/><lb n="19"/>ṣa<surplus>ṁ</surplus>ṣṭi-varṣa-sahasrāṇi</l>
          <l n="b">svargge modati bhūmidaḥ</l>
          <l n="c">Acchettā cānumaṁ<lb break="no" n="20"/>t<surplus>t</surplus>ā ca</l>
          <l n="d">tā<surplus>ṁ</surplus>ny eva narake vaset</l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="4">
          <l n="a">bahubhir vvasudhā dattā</l>
          <l n="b">rāja<surplus>ḥbh</surplus>bhis sa<lb break="no" n="21"/>garādibhiḥ</l>
          <l n="c">yasya yasya yadā bhūmis</l>
          <l n="d">tasya tasya tadā <lb n="22"/>phala<surplus>ṁ</surplus>m</l>
        </lg>
        <p>iti<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> sva-mukhājñayā| U<choice>
            <sic>kt</sic>
            <corr>tk</corr>
          </choice>īrṇṇaṁ Acalasiṅghena<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><!--
L22. daṇḍa: one horizontal stroke and one dot above, one below.
--><lb n="23"/>pravarddhamāna-vijaya-saṁv<surplus>v</surplus>atsara pa<surplus>ṁ</surplus>ñca <num value="5">5</num> kārttika-diso <num value="5">5</num><!--
D. Balogh: Sircar suggests emending diso to divasāḥ. I wonder; diso seems like a very strange mistake. Could we have a weekday here? di for divasa or dina and so for soma? Probably not though, I guess the weekday would come after the number.
--></p>
